Any agent that affects hormone levels and exerts antineoplastic effects. Antineoplastic hormonal/endocrine agents treat either hormone-dependent or hormone-sensitive cancers by modulating hormone levels and manipulating the endocrine system.
Any radiopharmaceutical agent that targets cancer cells and exerts an antineoplastic effect through radiotoxicity.
A bone of the leg (lower extremity).

Any agent that is capable of modulating the immune system in order to exert antineoplastic effects. Antineoplastic immunomodulating agents either activate the immune system, restore certain immune system activators or abrogate immunosuppression.

Any agent that has a biological nature, such as agents containing living organisms, derived from living organisms, or comprised of ex vivo synthesized analogs of substances derived from living organisms, and that exerts antineoplastic activity.
Any type of antibody that exerts antineoplastic activity.
Any tumor-targeting antibody conjugated to a cytotoxic agent that exerts an antineoplastic effect.
Any agent that inhibits the activity of any protein that is involved in cancer-specific pathways. An antineoplastic protein inhibitor is a specific cancer cell-targeting agent.

Any agent that specifically inhibits a particular enzyme that is overexpressed and/or mutated in cancer cell pathways. Antineoplastic enzyme inhibitors specifically target tumor cells by targeting enzymes that are not normally expressed or are minimally expressed in normal, healthy tissues.
Any immune cell-based preparation that can be used or may potentially be used for its cytotoxic activity against cancer cells.
A transitional cell carcinoma which is not amenable to surgical resection.
A carcinoma that arises from transitional cells and has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.
A mutation that occurs on both alleles of a single gene.
A bone of the arm (upper extremity).
A mutation that occurs on one allele of a gene.
A molecular genetic abnormality indicating the presence of a mutation in exon 9 of the CALR gene.

A molecular genetic abnormality indicating the presence of a deletion mutation in exon 9 of the CALR gene. These deletion mutations are associated with primary myelofibrosis and may be predicative of a favorable survival prognosis.

A molecular genetic abnormality indicating the presence of an insertion mutation in exon 9 of the CALR gene. These insertion mutations are associated with primary myelofibrosis and may be predicative of shortened survival.
A deletion of 52 nucleotides from the coding sequence of the CALR gene from positions 1092 through 1143.
An insertion of five nucleotides, TTGTC, between positions 1154 and 1155 of the coding sequence of the CALR gene.
A variation in the amino acid sequence for the calreticulin protein.

A change in the amino acid composition of the calreticulin protein where a frameshift mutation results in the insertion of 45 non-canonic amino acids followed by a stop codon immediately after the leucine residue at position 367.

A change in the amino acid composition of the calreticulin protein where a frameshift mutation results in the insertion of 46 non-canonic amino acids followed by a stop codon immediately after the lysine residue at position 385.
Any agent that directly targets the apoptotic pathway and has an antineoplastic effect.
One of the nodes that lie along the course of a lymphatic vessel between a primary melanoma site and a recognized node field. (from Medscape)
This gene plays a role in protein hormone signaling.

Human CGA wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 6q14.3 and is approximately 10 kb in length. This allele, which encodes glycoprotein hormones alpha chain protein, is involved in protein hormone-dependent signaling.
Glycoprotein hormones alpha chain (116 aa, ~13 kDa) is encoded by the human CGA gene. This protein plays a role in hormone signaling.
This gene is involved in detoxification of arylamine-containing compounds.

Human NAT1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 8p22 and is approximately 53 kb in length. This allele, which encodes arylamine N-acetyltransferase 1 protein, plays a role in the metabolism of arylamines.
Arylamine N-acetyltransferase 1 (290 aa, ~34 kDa) is encoded by the human NAT1 gene. This protein is involved in arylamine detoxification.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of hormone signaling.

Human INHBE wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 12q13.3 and is approximately 7 kb in length. This allele, which encodes inhibin beta E chain protein, is involved in the modulation of hormone secretion.
Inhibin beta E chain (350 aa, ~39 kDa) is encoded by the human INHBE gene. This protein plays a role in the secretion of hormones.
This gene is involved in electron transport.
A stem cell derived from embryonic sources or found in adult neural tissue. It has the capacity to generate all the multiple cell types found in the brain and spinal cord.

Human CYCS wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 7p15.3 and is approximately 7 kb in length. This allele, which encodes cytochrome c protein, plays a role in the mitochondrial electron transport chain. Mutation of the gene is associated with thrombocytopenia 4.
